@node "WhatUseHasThisCrapThing" "What is this?"

@{b} It looks nice, but WHAT is it?@{ub}

Err. Well. If you don't know what @{b}Shadowrun@{ub} or @{b}Matrix@{ub} is, then I'm afraid you have been fooled. You should have read the readme file, anyway. Ofcourse it could also be that you've read some cyberpunk novels (esp "Neuromancer") and recognised the word @{b}Matrix@{ub}, and thought that this is a game offering you a true 3D texture mapped sight of the@{b} Matrix@{ub}, etc. But alas, then you are fooled as well.

But for all you chummers out there, who are well aware of what the @{b}Matrix@{ub} is: this is a @{fg shine}Security DataSheaf Generator@{fg shadow}@{fg text} for the second edition of the @{b}Shadowrun Matrix@{ub} rules. (I know, I know, the name of the program isn't exactly correct, but you'll have to admit it sounds more appealing than "Security DataSheaf Generator" (which would probably lead to even more misunderstandings).

Now, go back to @{"<contents>" link "Main" 0} and learn how to use it.
@endnode

@node "Use" "Agreed. Now I know what it is, but I cannot use it."


                                 @{b}@{u}TUTORIAL@{ub}@{uu}

@{u}1. Installation@{uu}

No special files are required to run this program, apart from @{"MUI" LINK "Mui"}, that is. Unpack the archive to any directory you want.

@{u}2. Starting up.@{uu}

Go to wherever you've unpacked the archive to and type 'MatGen', omitting the quotes.

Usage: MatGen D=DEBUG/S

When the DEBUG switch is specified, MatGen will print relevant debugging information to a CON: window. See @{"<Bugs>" LINK "Bugs"} for details.

@{u}3. Using the program.@{@{uu}@{uu}

Set the Intrusion Difficulty (Keyboard ShortCut: i) and the Host Security Code (Keyboard ShortCut: s) and click on Create (Keyboard ShortCut: c). A DataSheaf will pop up. Now you can save ("Save Datasheaf") or print ("Print Datasheaf") it. Hard, or what? If you're not pleased with the result, just Create another Sheaf.

---
NB: Clicking "Create" while the Datasheaf window is still open will fill in the new datasheaf in the same window, ie the dimensions will not change. This could bother very picky people. If you are that kind of human, then close the DataSheaf window before creating another one.

NB: Printing consists of a direct dump through "PRT:". Printing has not been tested, but I cannot see why it should ever fail.   

@endnode

@node "Bugs" "Bugs... Or how to recognise a truly great piece of software" 

                               "What bugs?" 
                                       -- The Author.


@{b}
@{b}1. Hey! Wot a lousy programmer you are! It doesn't make it's own PartyIC.@{ub}

Yes yes, ok, I know. Maybe I will, one day, include an IC constellation constructor.

@{b}2. What is that DEBUG switch?@{ub}

It's a tool for me (and, incidentally for you too) to check whether MatGen is compliant with the Virtual Realities 2.0 rules. To see how it works, let's look at an example output. (NB: An easy way of assuring a debug log is by starting up MatGen like this: 'MatGen DEBUG >filename'. All debugging info will then be streamed or piped into the specified file. But I guess you knew that already.)

For terms etcetera, see p159ff. of VR 2.0

Modifier=4. @{i}This is the modifier derived from the host Security Code@{ui}
Easy/Blue/4 --> Min/Max Gap between steps=5/7.
@{i}Intrusion Difficulty/Security (Color) Code/Security Value@{ui}
------
Trigger Step=5 ; # Steps=1.
@{i}This is self-explanatory.@{ui}
Modified Roll=3.
@{i}The roll to determine which type of IC is triggered.@{ui}
Reactive White [IC rating:  4]
@{i}Type of IC and its rating.@{ui}

... @{i}And so on.@{ui}

This debugging option is very basic, but that is because it initially only was implemented for own usage. I decided to leave it in the final executable, just because, well, it does no harm, does it?

@{b}3. Strange characters appear upon loading the DataSheaf is some editors.@{ub}

Yes. That is true. I don't know why, but it appears MUI's control codes aren't very err... @{i}universal@{ui}. I hoped the logs would turn out to be ANSI texts with the control codes in it, but alas. Mind that PPMore and the DirOpus reader (to name a few) read the Sheafs without a problem.

If you'd like me to remove the control codes, or perhaps include an option to (de)activate them, tell @{"me" LINK "Moi"}.

There are undoubtedly more bugs (remember,@{i} I @{ui}have written this), but I haven't found them yet. Report to @{"me" LINK "Moi"} if you do.

@endnode

